[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:aws-cloudformation/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
